What a Lean Experiment Is
A lean experiment is a structured Build-Measure-Learn loop designed to validate or invalidate one specific hypothesis with the smallest possible build. Five parts:

Hypothesis — A testable claim. Format: "We believe [user] will [behavior] because [reason]. We'll know we're right when [measurable signal]." If you can't fill in the blanks, you don't have a hypothesis — you have a wish.
Riskiest Assumption — The single belief that, if wrong, kills the hypothesis. (Same thing we're working on right now in Step 1 of MVP.)
Test Design — The cheapest, fastest thing that produces real signal. Often not code: landing pages, concierge MVPs, fake doors, Wizard-of-Oz, smoke tests. Code is expensive — use it last.
Success Criteria — Defined before the test runs. Numeric, time-bound, falsifiable. No moving goalposts after data lands.
Decision Rule — Persevere / Pivot / Kill. Decide now what each outcome means, so you don't rationalize a bad result later.
The key discipline: if you can't tell me what data would make you abandon the idea, you're not running an experiment — you're seeking confirmation.

Common Cheap-Test Patterns
Pattern	What it tests	Cost
Landing page + waitlist	Demand / messaging	1 day
Fake door (button that says "coming soon")	Intent to use a feature	hours
Concierge MVP (you do it manually, no software)	Whether the outcome is valuable	days
Wizard of Oz (looks automated, humans behind curtain)	Whether the UX/output is acceptable	days
Smoke test ad (run ads, measure click/signup)	Targeting + value prop	$50–500
Pre-sell (take real money before building)	Willingness to pay (the hardest signal)	days
For an exec email summarizer, a concierge MVP is almost certainly the right first move: forward your test execs' inbox to a human (you) who writes summaries by hand for 5 days. If they don't read your hand-crafted summaries, they'll never read AI ones — and you've spent a week, not a quarter.

