Shipping on time and on budget is output success. It tells you Engineering executed well. It tells you exactly nothing about whether the feature does anything.

This is the trap Lean Startup was written to expose: teams celebrate the build, not the learning. "We shipped" is the moment the experiment starts, not the moment it ends.

What's Actually Being Celebrated
What you have	What you don't have
The thing exists	Anyone uses it
It works in prod	It changes user behavior
Engineering hit dates	The riskiest assumption was validated
Burn rate held	Anyone would pay for it / renew because of it
PMs can demo it	Anyone asked for more
If the feature ships and adoption is 3%, retention curves don't move, NPS is flat, and the business outcome you targeted (activation? retention? upgrades?) doesn't budge — you didn't win, you just spent the budget efficiently building the wrong thing efficiently. That's worse than over-budget-but-validated, because it looks like success and rewards the same behavior next quarter.

What a Real Win Looks Like
Before the celebration, I want to see:

The success criteria you defined before the build (you did define them, right? — Step 2 of MVP). Did you hit them?
The riskiest assumption — was it validated, invalidated, or are we still guessing?
The leading-indicator metric in the first 2-4 weeks of real exposure (adoption rate, return-use rate, qualitative "would you be disappointed if this went away?" survey à la Sean Ellis). Not "users praised it in Slack" — measurable signal.
The decision — Persevere, Pivot, or Kill — based on the data. If everything always says "persevere," you don't have a decision rule, you have a sunk-cost machine.
