      "response": "Now we're talking — pricing validation is where Lean earns its keep, because the cost of being wrong is huge (build a tier nobody upgrades to) and the cost of being right is huge (recurring revenue). And critically: "priority support" isn't really a feature — it's a service tier. Build cost is near zero. So the only thing left to validate is willingness to pay. That's pure assumption-test territory.

The Pricing-Validation Hierarchy (Weakest → Strongest Signal)
Method	What it tests	Real money?	Signal strength	Time
Survey: "Would you pay $20/mo?"	Stated preference	No	⭐ Near useless	1 day
Van Westendorp / Gabor-Granger pricing survey	Sensitivity range	No	⭐⭐ Decent ceiling/floor	1 wk
Landing page + "Upgrade" CTA	Click-intent	No	⭐⭐ Curiosity ≠ purchase	1 wk
Fake door ("Upgrade for $20/mo" → "Joining waitlist")	Click-through to pay	No	⭐⭐⭐ Decent intent	1 wk
Smoke email to existing customers ("Reply to opt in, we'll bill $20/mo")	Reply rate from your actual base	Almost	⭐⭐⭐⭐ Strong	days
Pre-sell (real Stripe checkout, real card charge)	Actual conversion	Yes	⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Strongest pre-build	1-2 wk
Concierge MVP (you deliver priority support by hand, charge $20/mo, watch 60-day renewal)	Conversion + retention	Yes	⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Best total signal	4-8 wk
The cardinal rule: stated preference is worthless. SMBs will tell you "yes I'd pay $20/mo for that" all day long, then not click upgrade when you ship it. Only money in the bank counts. The literature is brutal here — typical gap between "I would pay" and "I did pay" is 5–10x.

What I'd Actually Run
A two-track parallel test, ~3 weeks, near-zero build:

Track A: Pre-sell to existing customers (intent at scale)
Email a random 10-20% sample of your SMB base (not all — preserve a control)
"We're piloting Priority Support for SMB customers — guaranteed first-response in 1 hour, dedicated Slack channel, monthly check-in call. $20/mo, billed on enrollment. Reply YES to join the beta cohort starting [date]."
Send to a real Stripe checkout. Take real money on day one. No "we'll bill you later." No waitlist trick.
Measure: reply rate → click-to-checkout → conversion → 30-day refund/cancel rate
Track B: Concierge delivery to the converters (retention reality check)
The customers who pay get the white-glove service — but you (or 1-2 people) deliver it manually. No queue system, no SLA tooling, no automation. Slack channel, calendar invites, fast-response inbox.
Run for 60 days. Measure: do they use it? Do they renew at day 30? Day 60? Do they tell anyone?
Why both tracks
Track A tells you whether SMBs convert (acquisition signal).
Track B tells you whether they value it once they have it (retention signal — far more important for a recurring tier).
A customer who pays $20 once and churns at month 2 is not validation. A pricing tier dies on retention, not conversion.
Define Success Criteria Before The Test (this is non-negotiable)
Metric	Threshold	Source
Email-to-conversion rate	≥ 3% of contacted SMB customers actually pay	Stripe
30-day cancel/refund rate	≤ 15%	Stripe
60-day renewal	≥ 70%	Stripe
Unprompted usage (Slack messages, support tickets touched)	≥ 60% of cohort uses it ≥ 2x in month 1	Manual
Qualitative: "Very disappointed if removed"	≥ 40% (Sean Ellis cut)	5-question survey at day 30
If three or more of these miss, kill the tier or pivot the offering (different price, different bundle of benefits, different segment). Decide now — not after you've grown attached to the data.

Common Traps
Free-trial-as-validation. "We gave 50 customers free priority support and they loved it!" Of course they did — it was free. Free signal is noise. Charge from minute one.
Testing on enthusiasts. Sampling your power users tells you what power users want, not what your modal SMB wants. Random-sample your base.
Bundling the test. "We'll launch priority support and a few other things and see if revenue moves." You'll learn nothing about which lever moved what. Test the tier in isolation.
Anchoring too low. $20/mo is cheap enough that some SMBs will buy it impulsively. Watch 60-day renewal, not week-1 conversion. The real question is whether they re-up when the second invoice hits.
Sunk-cost rationalization. "Conversion was 1.8% but the qualitative feedback was great, let's build it anyway." This is how dead tiers get born. Pre-commit the decision rule.
Price testing with no value validation. If concierge delivery is exhausting and customers churn fast, the answer isn't a lower price — it's that priority support isn't a tier they want. $0/mo wouldn't fix it.
What You Don't Need To Build To Run This
No new product code. None.
No SLA tooling. Manual is fine for the cohort size.
No upgrade flow in-app. Stripe payment link in an email works.
No fancy dashboard. A spreadsheet tracking each customer's interactions and renewal status is enough for n ≤ 50.
You can have this test running in 5-7 business days and decisions in hand in 9-10 weeks for the cost of two people's part-time attention — versus a full quarter of engineering effort building a tier nobody buys.

