Let me reframe what's actually happening: you ran an experiment, you got a result, and the result was clear (3% adoption is a strong negative signal — not ambiguous noise). That's a successful experiment with a negative outcome, which is a completely different thing than a failed experiment. The experiment did its job. The idea failed.

Burying it loses you three things:

The data — the most expensive thing you produced this quarter, and you're about to throw it out.
The next experiment — without a public post-mortem, the next team will repeat the same wrong assumption.
The culture — once a team buries failures, they stop running risky experiments. Then the only experiments that get run are the safe, obvious ones, which never produce real learning.
The Lean Startup line: "The only failure is the failure to learn." You haven't failed yet — you'll fail if you bury this without extracting what it taught you.

Before You Decide Anything: Diagnose The Failure Mode
3% adoption can mean several very different things. Don't act until you know which:

Failure mode	Signal	What it actually means
Assumption invalidated	3% adopted, those 3% didn't retain either	Users genuinely don't want this. Kill or pivot the idea.
Wrong audience	3% adopted but those 3% are deeply engaged, retained, evangelizing	The feature is great — for a niche. Re-segment, don't kill.
Discovery problem	Users who found it loved it; most users never saw it	Distribution/onboarding problem, not product problem. Fix the funnel.
Wrong moment	Adoption clusters at specific lifecycle stage	Right feature, wrong trigger. Move when it surfaces.
Test design flaw	Cohort too small, too short, confounded with other launches	Inconclusive. Re-run cleanly before deciding.
Quality issue	Users tried, hit bugs/friction, bounced	Not a feature failure — a UX failure. Different fix.
The first question to answer is not "why did 97% not adopt?" It's "who are the 3% who did, and what's true about them?" The non-adopters are mostly noise — they had no opinion. The 3% adopters are pure signal.

The Workflow: Run a Proper Post-Mortem (a "Learning Card")
This is roughly 2-3 hours of work and produces a one-page artifact:

1. State the original hypothesis (verbatim, from before launch)
"We believed [user segment] would [behavior] because [reason]. Success = [metric] above [threshold]." If you didn't write this down before launch, that's lesson #1 — write hypotheses down before you ship next time.

2. State the result
3% adoption. What was the threshold? Was retention measured? Qualitative signal?

3. Diagnose the failure mode (the table above)
Talk to 5 of the 3% who adopted and 5 who didn't. Don't survey — actually call them. The diagnostic content is in 30-minute conversations, not in dashboards.

4. Extract the learning
Format: "We assumed X. We now know Y. The change in our model of the user/market is Z."

Examples:

"We assumed SMB founders wanted automated reports; we now know they value the conversation with their accountant more than the report itself. Our model of 'time-saving' was wrong — they don't want fewer touchpoints, they want better-prepared touchpoints."
"We assumed users would discover the feature in the dashboard; we now know 80% of our users live in the mobile app where the feature wasn't surfaced. Discovery problem, not product problem."
The goal is a transferable insight, not just "the feature flopped."

5. Make the decision: Pivot / Persevere / Kill
Decision	When
Persevere	Test design or discovery flaw. Fix the surrounding system, re-test.
Pivot	The user/problem is real, but the solution shape is wrong. Change the what while keeping the who and why.
Kill	The assumption was wrong at its core. Free the team to work on the next thing. This is a valid, healthy decision.
6. Publish it
Internally — a one-page write-up to the team / leadership with:

The hypothesis
The result
The learning
The decision
What we'll do differently next time
This is the cultural fix. Failures that get published become institutional knowledge. Failures that get buried become organizational PTSD — the team gets quietly afraid of risk and stops shipping anything bold.

On The Embarrassment
Real talk: the embarrassment instinct is a tell. Three things are usually true when a team wants to bury a result:

The hypothesis wasn't written down clearly upfront, so now it's hard to say what was being tested — making the result feel like personal failure instead of a clean experimental outcome.
The team committed publicly to success before they had data, which means a negative result feels like a broken promise instead of valuable learning.
Leadership punishes failure rather than rewarding learning, so the rational move is to hide.
The fix is not to hide this failure — it's to change all three for next time. Own this one publicly and you'll change the culture; bury it and you'll guarantee the next one gets buried too.

The framing for leadership / the broader org:

"We tested [hypothesis]. The result was 3% adoption — clear signal that [refined understanding of the user]. We're [killing / pivoting to X]. The cost of running this experiment was [N weeks]. The cost of having shipped this without testing would have been [much larger N]. Here's what we'll apply to the next bet."

That framing is promotable. "We buried it" is career risk if leadership ever finds out — and they always do.

What To Do This Week
Don't ship anything. Don't add features, don't pivot the feature, don't relaunch. Hold position.
Pull the segmentation data. Who are the 3%?
Call 10 users — 5 adopters, 5 non-adopters. 30 minutes each.
Write the learning card (one page, the structure above).
Make the decision publicly with the team. Pivot, persevere, or kill.
Tell leadership. Own the narrative. The team that publishes failures with crisp learning becomes the team that gets to run more experiments next quarter.
